  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Record of the Jade-Green Pavilion
  author: An Jin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since the year I turned fifteen, I have sat reading in a thatched cottage, ignorant of the four directions for a decade past. In the autumn of the year Jeongsa, traveling toward the capital to take the civil examinations, I first beheld the Floating Jade Pavilion at Yeongmyeong Temple on the road through Pyongyang. Five years later, serving as magistrate of Jinyang, I ascended the Champion's Pavilion at Yongdu Temple. I thought to myself that in all my years, no northern or southern vista had exceeded these two towers.

    Yesterday, on official business bound for Jiangyang, I glimpsed a pavilion along the way. Its eaves and pillars seemed to dance in flight; its vermillion paintings blazed like a phoenix soaring through half the sky. I turned to my companion and asked, "When was that tower built, and who chose its site?" He replied, "The present magistrate has just completed its construction." Delighted at this news, I crossed by boat and climbed to the railings. From every direction, the landscape and mountains rivaled those two earlier towers, and in the brilliance of its decoration, it surpassed them.

    Alas! Since this province has existed, these mountains have stood. Many heroes and great men have come to govern here, yet none before has carved into emerald cliffs and raised a tower above clear waters. Only this magistrate has achieved it. Is this not Heaven's creation and Earth's keeping, bestowed upon the worthy?

    Thereupon I raised my cup and sang:

    White clouds drift through sapphire peaks,
    The bright moon rises over jade waters.
    From this tower, four seasons never tire the watching eye—
    My distant longing reaches toward the edge of Heaven.

    Though mountains crumble and waters dry,
    The magistrate's virtue shall not be forgotten.

    My companion said, "This song should be written down as the record of this tower." I took brush in hand and wrote it. As for the plans and improvements, and all particulars great and small worthy of observation, these await the discernment of one skilled in verse. There is no hurry.

    Who named this tower the Jade-Green Pavilion? The magistrate himself. And who is this magistrate? The son of the noble Jin, whose family has served as ministers through generations—a descendant of the Lord of Sangnak.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Floating Jade Pavilion (浮碧樓) and Champion's Pavilion (狀元樓) were famous viewing towers that the author had previously visited, serving as aesthetic and architectural precedents for his judgment.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'four directions' (四方) is a classical expression referring to the wider world beyond one's immediate locality.
  - key: ''
    value: The song employs traditional imagery of clouds, moon, and water to express both the beauty of the setting and the permanence of virtue, a common motif in Korean literary records of buildings.
